01:04:49.420 --> 01:04:53.110
Times crossword puzzle, if it's
hashed, and the hashes match,

01:04:53.110 --> 01:04:54.250
voil.

01:04:54.250 --> 01:04:57.610
You solved The New York
Times crossword puzzle.

01:04:57.610 --> 01:05:02.480
So you can have commitment
schemes for the data.

01:05:02.480 --> 01:05:04.190
And it can be distributed.

01:05:04.190 --> 01:05:06.220
Yes, Joequinn.

01:05:06.220 --> 01:05:09.040
AUDIENCE: So even
if it's append-only,

01:05:09.040 --> 01:05:11.700
if you take away
the proof of work,

01:05:11.700 --> 01:05:16.930
you can rewrite it in
a very quick manner.

01:05:16.930 --> 01:05:19.700
PROFESSOR: So Joequinn's
raising a very important point.

01:05:19.700 --> 01:05:23.940
So even if it's append-only,
you get rid of proof of work,

01:05:23.940 --> 01:05:26.700
can't somebody go
in and rewrite it?

01:05:26.700 --> 01:05:33.480
Permissioned blockchains make
a different trade-off on trust.

01:05:33.480 --> 01:05:36.630
Permissionless system say,
we're going to address trust

01:05:36.630 --> 01:05:38.850
through this proof of work.

01:05:38.850 --> 01:05:42.480
And at least 51% of
all of the network

01:05:42.480 --> 01:05:46.370
has to, in essence, agree
and validate, and the like.

01:05:46.370 --> 01:05:47.970
Permissioned
basically are saying,

01:05:47.970 --> 01:05:53.780
I'm going to trust
the 10 or 15 or 20

01:05:53.780 --> 01:05:58.750
nodes that are in the system
can validate against each other.

01:05:58.750 --> 01:06:03.980
And so there's something
about the club that's

01:06:03.980 --> 01:06:06.260
authorized in the network.

01:06:06.260 --> 01:06:08.390
But they're still
using append-only.

01:06:08.390 --> 01:06:10.610
You're right that
within those 20,

01:06:10.610 --> 01:06:13.250
somebody could try to
rush through and do

01:06:13.250 --> 01:06:16.190
a whole entire new append-only.

01:06:16.190 --> 01:06:22.345
But then within the
club, it's exposed.

01:06:22.345 --> 01:06:24.640
AUDIENCE: If the club
agrees that the last two

01:06:24.640 --> 01:06:29.110
days have to be rewritten, they
can do it in a very easy way.

01:06:29.110 --> 01:06:30.100
PROFESSOR: Correct.

01:06:30.100 --> 01:06:32.650
But I would contend
that even in Bitcoin,

01:06:32.650 --> 01:06:36.490
if 10,000 nodes decided to
rewrite the last two days,

01:06:36.490 --> 01:06:38.220
they could.

01:06:38.220 --> 01:06:38.720
It's a--

01:06:38.720 --> 01:06:41.265
AUDIENCE: Taken a lot of
time, because they have--

01:06:41.265 --> 01:06:41.890
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:06:41.890 --> 01:06:42.837
AUDIENCE: --to find--

01:06:42.837 --> 01:06:43.920
PROFESSOR: That's correct.

01:06:43.920 --> 01:06:44.580
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:06:44.580 --> 01:06:45.663
PROFESSOR: That's correct.

01:06:45.663 --> 01:06:47.940
So what Joequinn's
saying is in Bitcoin,

01:06:47.940 --> 01:06:51.270
what protects against that
is partly the proof of work,

01:06:51.270 --> 01:06:55.320
and partly that it takes
10,000, or at least 51% of them,

01:06:55.320 --> 01:06:58.740
probably, to rewrite
the last two days.

01:06:58.740 --> 01:07:00.690
The economic
incentives in Bitcoin

01:07:00.690 --> 01:07:04.980
is, is why waste all your
computer power and electricity

01:07:04.980 --> 01:07:09.880
and so forth doing that when
you may as well just go forward?

01:07:09.880 --> 01:07:14.050
I think Bitcoin could be
susceptible to state actors.

01:07:14.050 --> 01:07:17.010
I think, you know, if
North Korea wanted--

01:07:17.010 --> 01:07:21.210
or Russia wanted-- to spend
probably single digit billions,

01:07:21.210 --> 01:07:24.870
but at most maybe 10 billion,
they could overwhelm the whole

01:07:24.870 --> 01:07:27.270
system and bring--

01:07:27.270 --> 01:07:29.790
they could do a 51%
attack by buying up

01:07:29.790 --> 01:07:34.700
enough mining
equipment, the ASICs,

01:07:34.700 --> 01:07:37.850
and just bigfooting
the whole system.

01:07:37.850 --> 01:07:40.800
But it's multiple billio-- and
there's academic papers on this

01:07:40.800 --> 01:07:41.300
now.

01:07:41.300 --> 01:07:42.920
It's single digit billions.

01:07:42.920 --> 01:07:45.740
A state actor could--

01:07:45.740 --> 01:07:47.330
an individual wouldn't
want to do it,

01:07:47.330 --> 01:07:51.680
because you'd crush $110 billion
market cap down to [INAUDIBLE]..

01:07:51.680 --> 01:07:53.885
So that would be kind of unwise.

01:07:57.860 --> 01:08:02.300
This is a very critical part
of what a private blockchain--

01:08:02.300 --> 01:08:04.850
to me, economically,
what a private blockchain

01:08:04.850 --> 01:08:09.200
can do and facilitate better
than a traditional database.

01:08:09.200 --> 01:08:11.630
I'm not saying this
list is the only list.

01:08:11.630 --> 01:08:14.990
I'm not even saying this list
is completely the right list.

01:08:14.990 --> 01:08:17.600
This is Gary
Gensler's list trying

01:08:17.600 --> 01:08:20.600
to say, what's the
business that separates

01:08:20.600 --> 01:08:22.340
traditional blockchains?

01:08:22.340 --> 01:08:25.540
Append-only timestamping.

01:08:25.540 --> 01:08:29.020
Some cryptography
and schemes that

01:08:29.020 --> 01:08:35.080
makes the data immutable so
you can put it in a ledger--

01:08:35.080 --> 01:08:37.630
so it's back to
ledgers and so forth--

01:08:37.630 --> 01:08:40.069
and thus, finality
of settlement.

01:08:40.069 --> 01:08:43.660
Does anybody want to remind the
class what settlement means?

01:08:46.859 --> 01:08:47.510
Anybody?

01:08:47.510 --> 01:08:49.990
Take a shot.

01:08:49.990 --> 01:08:52.147
Where's my accountant?

01:08:52.147 --> 01:08:55.270
Aviva's not here.

01:08:55.270 --> 01:08:56.150
Oh, please.

01:08:58.705 --> 01:09:02.633
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
do with the UTXO.

01:09:02.633 --> 01:09:04.970
PROFESSOR: No,
forget about UTXO.

01:09:04.970 --> 01:09:06.859
Just tell me what
settlement means.

01:09:06.859 --> 01:09:09.865
AUDIENCE: Oh, like, making
off your debit and credit.

01:09:09.865 --> 01:09:12.229
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
debits and credits.

01:09:12.229 --> 01:09:18.420
Settlement means changing
the data in a ledger,

01:09:18.420 --> 01:09:21.720
and doing it with finality.

01:09:21.720 --> 01:09:26.120
In essence, do I
have $10 or $11?

01:09:26.120 --> 01:09:30.569
A payment settlement system
is when you finally say,

01:09:30.569 --> 01:09:33.390
I've got $11, no longer $10.

01:09:33.390 --> 01:09:38.930
And Amanda's got
$9 instead of $10.

01:09:38.930 --> 01:09:39.649
You went down.

01:09:39.649 --> 01:09:40.409
I went up.

01:09:40.409 --> 01:09:41.170
Is that all right?

01:09:41.170 --> 01:09:42.050
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:09:42.050 --> 01:09:43.870
PROFESSOR: Thank you.

01:09:43.870 --> 01:09:46.210
You'll hear a lot about
clearing and settlement.

01:09:46.210 --> 01:09:48.880
The word settlement
means to finally change

01:09:48.880 --> 01:09:52.029
the data in a ledger,
and that we're not

01:09:52.029 --> 01:09:53.830
going to come back to it.

01:09:53.830 --> 01:09:54.750
It's done.

01:09:54.750 --> 01:09:56.680
It's final.

01:09:56.680 --> 01:09:58.600
If we're moving
something of value--

01:09:58.600 --> 01:10:01.580
and the value could be grapes.

01:10:01.580 --> 01:10:03.080
The value could be diamonds.

01:10:03.080 --> 01:10:04.490
The value can be real estate.

01:10:04.490 --> 01:10:05.780
The value can be money.

01:10:05.780 --> 01:10:08.000
But if we're moving
something of value

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:16.440
and storing it on a ledger, it's
more adaptable to blockchain.

01:10:16.440 --> 01:10:18.960
If you're doing
some database that

01:10:18.960 --> 01:10:21.840
has nothing to do with
things of value and ledger,

01:10:21.840 --> 01:10:26.250
you don't need final
immutable settlement.

01:10:26.250 --> 01:10:28.530
I would contend you
probably have less reason

01:10:28.530 --> 01:10:30.420
to use any of this
blockchain stuff.

01:10:32.940 --> 01:10:33.610
Zan.

01:10:33.610 --> 01:10:35.620
AUDIENCE: Can you
maybe talk a little bit

01:10:35.620 --> 01:10:38.050
about a real-world
implementation of this?

01:10:38.050 --> 01:10:41.470
So I saw recently that Walmart
is forcing their suppliers

01:10:41.470 --> 01:10:45.840
to basically add themselves
into this private blockchain

01:10:45.840 --> 01:10:48.198
to basically track
their supply chain.

01:10:48.198 --> 01:10:49.990
I'm having a really
hard time understanding

01:10:49.990 --> 01:10:52.240
why that needs to
be on a blockchain,

01:10:52.240 --> 01:10:54.010
whether permissioned
or nonpermissioned,

01:10:54.010 --> 01:10:56.920
and why that needs to be.

01:10:56.920 --> 01:10:59.500
PROFESSOR: So the question
is, why is Walmart

01:10:59.500 --> 01:11:02.290
putting supply chain with a
bunch of agricultural products

01:11:02.290 --> 01:11:03.910
on a blockchain?

01:11:03.910 --> 01:11:08.255
Agricultural products
are something of value,

01:11:08.255 --> 01:11:13.020
whether it's corn,
wheat, grapes.

01:11:13.020 --> 01:11:14.490
It's something of value.

01:11:14.490 --> 01:11:18.700
And when it moves from one
owner to another owner,

01:11:18.700 --> 01:11:20.200
if you keep that
on a ledger, you

01:11:20.200 --> 01:11:23.350
can record that
Amanda has the grapes,

01:11:23.350 --> 01:11:26.450
and Gary no longer
has the grapes.

01:11:26.450 --> 01:11:31.770
And another thing that
blockchains help with

01:11:31.770 --> 01:11:36.030
is they lower the cost of
reconciling multiple databases.

01:11:36.030 --> 01:11:39.780
We could keep-- as
in agriculture--

01:11:39.780 --> 01:11:44.280
we can keep separate
ledgers, separate databases.

01:11:44.280 --> 01:11:48.720
The farmers keeping
their database.

01:11:48.720 --> 01:11:50.970
The wholesaler with
the grain elevators

01:11:50.970 --> 01:11:54.240
are keeping their database,
and up the supply chain,

01:11:54.240 --> 01:11:56.280
from the farm, to
the grain elevator,

01:11:56.280 --> 01:11:58.950
to the millers and
merchants, all the way

01:11:58.950 --> 01:12:04.560
to General Mills, all the
way to Kroger and the store.

01:12:04.560 --> 01:12:08.400
Right now, those are multiple
databases that, by and large,

01:12:08.400 --> 01:12:10.470
don't have to communicate.

01:12:10.470 --> 01:12:14.070
So the question is, will
Walmart get to the place

01:12:14.070 --> 01:12:15.900
where that's a good idea?

01:12:15.900 --> 01:12:22.030
But I'm just pointing out if
you're moving things of value

01:12:22.030 --> 01:12:25.870
where you want to keep final
settlement that you know who

01:12:25.870 --> 01:12:29.650
owns that thing of
value in ledgers,

01:12:29.650 --> 01:12:33.620
and lastly, if you want to
lower any reconciliation--

01:12:37.840 --> 01:12:41.950
if you have multiple
ledgers and things of value,

01:12:41.950 --> 01:12:47.170
blockchain, I think,
is more valuable.

01:12:47.170 --> 01:12:49.448
Zan's asking, well,
is that Walmart?

01:12:49.448 --> 01:12:49.990
I don't know.

01:12:49.990 --> 01:12:51.090
We're going to find out.

01:12:51.090 --> 01:12:53.148
Tom, and I've got about
seven minutes to finish.

01:12:53.148 --> 01:12:54.690
AUDIENCE: There was
a talk last year.

01:12:54.690 --> 01:12:57.070
Somebody [INAUDIBLE] came
in and talked about the--

01:12:57.070 --> 01:12:59.050
they were then
piloting this program.

01:12:59.050 --> 01:13:01.780
But the example they used
was, in E. coli outbreak

01:13:01.780 --> 01:13:05.830
in their spinach supply, rather
than taking a whole supplier,

01:13:05.830 --> 01:13:08.050
an entire wholesaler
offline and recalling

01:13:08.050 --> 01:13:10.300
all of that product,
through the blockchain,

01:13:10.300 --> 01:13:12.760
they could trace it
to a particular farm

01:13:12.760 --> 01:13:16.030
and a single point of origin
almost instantaneously

01:13:16.030 --> 01:13:18.352
and just take off a much
smaller portion of it.

01:13:18.352 --> 01:13:19.560
PROFESSOR: So let me do this.

01:13:19.560 --> 01:13:20.320
Let me just-- hold on.

01:13:20.320 --> 01:13:21.885
I know we've got
two questions here.

01:13:21.885 --> 01:13:24.940
Let me just hold on, just
for-- is that all right?

01:13:24.940 --> 01:13:25.440
All right.

01:13:25.440 --> 01:13:26.660
We got permission.

01:13:26.660 --> 01:13:30.140
So this was what we
talked about earlier--

01:13:30.140 --> 01:13:34.430
Coase's trade-offs of costs.

01:13:34.430 --> 01:13:36.943
Let me try another
one, which is going

01:13:36.943 --> 01:13:41.310
to be my shot at blockchains
and traditional databases.

01:13:41.310 --> 01:13:43.980
So one is access control.

01:13:43.980 --> 01:13:45.870
Who has access to the ledger?

01:13:45.870 --> 01:13:50.060
Who has access, if I
might, to the data?

01:13:50.060 --> 01:13:53.180
Three different types of
approaches we talked about--

01:13:53.180 --> 01:13:56.420
open permissionless,
multiple permissioned,

01:13:56.420 --> 01:13:57.410
and client server.

01:13:57.410 --> 01:13:59.090
I'm using the word
client server just

01:13:59.090 --> 01:14:01.190
to say traditional database.

01:14:01.190 --> 01:14:03.200
You can use another words.

01:14:03.200 --> 01:14:06.530
But I'm just trying to say
three different types of data

01:14:06.530 --> 01:14:07.340
structures.

01:14:07.340 --> 01:14:09.410
And to Zan's question,
why would you

01:14:09.410 --> 01:14:11.420
be in one bucket versus another?

01:14:11.420 --> 01:14:12.710
And I'm saying this.

01:14:12.710 --> 01:14:15.170
If you're a venture
capitalist one day,

01:14:15.170 --> 01:14:18.890
and somebody comes in to you
with a blockchain solution,

01:14:18.890 --> 01:14:20.600
this is the same thing.

01:14:20.600 --> 01:14:22.400
Hopefully, you'll
make it better.

01:14:22.400 --> 01:14:24.890
This is just my approach to it.

01:14:24.890 --> 01:14:29.360
Public blockchain-- do
you need, basically,

01:14:29.360 --> 01:14:32.090
public write capability,
that lots of people

01:14:32.090 --> 01:14:34.550
can write to these ledgers?

01:14:34.550 --> 01:14:36.230
Do you need that somewhere?

01:14:36.230 --> 01:14:39.830
Secondly, do you want some peer
to peer transaction capability

01:14:39.830 --> 01:14:44.040
across the distributed ledger?

01:14:44.040 --> 01:14:46.155
Do you kind of not want
any central intermediary?

01:14:46.155 --> 01:14:48.030
Maybe you don't want
the central intermediary

01:14:48.030 --> 01:14:49.650
because they're
slow and sluggish.

01:14:49.650 --> 01:14:51.525
Maybe you don't want
the central intermediary

01:14:51.525 --> 01:14:53.520
because they have a
lot of economic rents.

01:14:53.520 --> 01:14:55.590
It doesn't matter to me
why you want to get rid

01:14:55.590 --> 01:14:57.072
of the central intermediary.

01:14:57.072 --> 01:14:59.280
But if you want to get rid
of a central intermediary,

01:14:59.280 --> 01:15:02.630
or lessen their control,
or lower their control,

01:15:02.630 --> 01:15:06.690
raise peer to peer transactions,
have a lot of public writing--

01:15:06.690 --> 01:15:09.810
oh, and by the way, if you
want some token economics,

01:15:09.810 --> 01:15:11.700
you're probably
somewhere over here.

01:15:11.700 --> 01:15:13.620
I'm not saying you
have to have all four.

01:15:13.620 --> 01:15:16.230
But to me, those are
the kind of three

01:15:16.230 --> 01:15:18.360
or four things that
are floating around

01:15:18.360 --> 01:15:21.520
why you might be over there.

01:15:21.520 --> 01:15:23.860
Private blockchains--
well, maybe you actually

01:15:23.860 --> 01:15:25.960
don't want public
write capability.

01:15:25.960 --> 01:15:27.050
You need private.

01:15:27.050 --> 01:15:32.110
Whether it's just the Australian
Stock Exchange or 15 to 20 club

01:15:32.110 --> 01:15:36.670
deal, you still want kind
of multiple people to write,

01:15:36.670 --> 01:15:39.550
but you want it to be private.

01:15:39.550 --> 01:15:46.670
But if you still need finality
of data and an append-only log,

01:15:46.670 --> 01:15:48.990
that you need this appending--

01:15:48.990 --> 01:15:53.090
the log, and you need
some public verifiability,

01:15:53.090 --> 01:15:55.880
that you still need that
data to be verified amongst--

01:15:55.880 --> 01:15:59.360
and this public means
15 or 20 players.

01:15:59.360 --> 01:16:02.280
But you need it to be
able to be verified--

01:16:02.280 --> 01:16:05.210
so the trust mechanism is
not thousands and open.

01:16:05.210 --> 01:16:08.330
The trust mechanism is
15 or 20 or 5 parties.

01:16:08.330 --> 01:16:09.530
But you still need it--

01:16:09.530 --> 01:16:11.600
you might be there.

01:16:11.600 --> 01:16:14.630
Where I come out is there's
some cases that you just

01:16:14.630 --> 01:16:17.470
don't need any of this.

01:16:17.470 --> 01:16:21.190
There's a trusted party
that hosts the data.

01:16:21.190 --> 01:16:23.920
Your trust mechanism
is one party.

01:16:23.920 --> 01:16:25.570
The trusted party can do the--

01:16:25.570 --> 01:16:27.460
I use the letters CRUD.

01:16:27.460 --> 01:16:36.390
That's the create, and update,
and delete, and so forth.

01:16:36.390 --> 01:16:40.400
And that's based on client
service architecture,

01:16:40.400 --> 01:16:42.170
this client server architecture.

01:16:42.170 --> 01:16:45.260
There's always, in that
circumstance, somebody right

01:16:45.260 --> 01:16:49.250
in the middle that
basically owns,

01:16:49.250 --> 01:16:54.130
updates, governs that
whole architecture.

01:16:54.130 --> 01:16:59.050
My business judgment
on this is if you're

01:16:59.050 --> 01:17:03.620
moving things of value, you
want those things to value

01:17:03.620 --> 01:17:08.340
to have some final
settlement and immutability.

01:17:08.340 --> 01:17:10.710
And immutability
append-only logs give you

01:17:10.710 --> 01:17:13.550
some of that final settlement.

01:17:13.550 --> 01:17:15.800
We talked very briefly
about a lawsuit

01:17:15.800 --> 01:17:19.690
that was 300 plus years ago--
the Crawford case in Scotland

01:17:19.690 --> 01:17:22.340
that you won't have to remember.

01:17:22.340 --> 01:17:25.820
But this-- watch this.

01:17:25.820 --> 01:17:27.380
So steal this from me.

01:17:27.380 --> 01:17:28.230
Just do me a favor.

01:17:28.230 --> 01:17:29.070
Just steal it.

01:17:29.070 --> 01:17:29.570
OK.

01:17:29.570 --> 01:17:31.610
Right now, I have
a right of action.

01:17:31.610 --> 01:17:34.310
But if you give it to-- who
are you going to give it to?

01:17:34.310 --> 01:17:37.780
I don't have any
rights against you.

01:17:37.780 --> 01:17:38.870
No.

01:17:38.870 --> 01:17:39.380
Well, wait.

01:17:39.380 --> 01:17:42.020
It depends whether he
knew you stole it from me.

01:17:42.020 --> 01:17:45.270
But it's gone.

01:17:45.270 --> 01:17:47.670
That's final settlement.

01:17:47.670 --> 01:17:50.250
Those $2 are gone.

01:17:50.250 --> 01:17:51.930
That's final settlement.

01:17:51.930 --> 01:17:52.770
It's immutable.

01:17:52.770 --> 01:17:54.270
I can't get them back.

01:17:54.270 --> 01:17:55.050
What, Christopher?

01:17:55.050 --> 01:17:55.820
You want them?

01:17:55.820 --> 01:17:57.570
AUDIENCE: I just was
asking for the money.

01:17:57.570 --> 01:17:59.550
PROFESSOR: You were
asking for the money.

